# Testing

- You MUST always write tests for your code
- You MUST write tests before your write the code (see [tdd.mdc](.cursor/rules/tdd.mdc) for TDD workflow)
- Use PHPUnit for unit and integration tests
- Tests MUST test positive and negative outcomes
- Run PHPUnit in the container `docker compose exec -T php sh -c "export XDEBUG_MODE=off && bin/console cache:clear && bin/phpunit"`
- Never test private methods
- Never test classes for being final or readonly
- Never try to mock final classes
- Use mocks and stubs to isolate tests
- Never test Input and Result transfer objects
- Never test two things in one test case, test only the method at hand
- All tests of a capability MUST have the `#[Group('<CapabilityName>')]` attribute with the name of the capability.
- Test methods MUST have the `#[Test]` attribute
- Test method names MUST NOT use the BDD-style `it` prefix (e.g. `itCanBeCreated`, `itThrowsWhenEmpty`). Use descriptive camelCase that starts with a lowercase verb or phrase, e.g. `canBeCreated`, `throwsWhenEmailIsEmpty`, `emitsSubscriptionWasCreatedEvent`.
- For tests that are the same but use different data use PHPUnit data providers
- Code that is tenant aware MUST have tests to check if the read or written data gets the tenant id applied correctly.
- Always run tests with `export XDEBUG_MODE=off`
- When you are done with your task run ALL tests, if there are errors fix them until all tests pass

## Test method naming

- Bulk cleanup of accidental `it*` test names: `php scripts/rename-it-prefixed-test-methods.php` from the backend project root (default: list renames; `--apply` rewrites files).

## Arrange, Act, Assert

- Every PHPUnit test method MUST use comments `// Arrange`, `// Act`, and `// Assert` to separate the three phases (at least once each per method).
- **Arrange** – fixtures, mocks, `KernelBrowser` / client, `login()`, and any prerequisite data or HTTP setup required before exercising the subject.
- **Act** – the call(s) that directly exercise the code under test (e.g. the use case invocation, repository method, or the primary HTTP request for that behavior). Prefer one clear Act block; if the scenario has distinct exercise-then-verify cycles, repeat `// Act` and `// Assert` in pairs for each cycle.
- **Assert** – expectations only (`assert*`), plus any follow-up reads or HTTP calls made solely to verify outcomes (e.g. `GET` after a `POST` to confirm persisted state).

## Test Base Classes

- **ApiTestCase** – for HTTP/API controller tests; provides `apiCall()`, `login()`, `loginBackendUser()`, `getFixtureGenerator()`, `assertResponseIsProblemJson()`
- **AppTestCase** – extends `ApiTestCase`; use for integration tests needing container, fixtures, tenant context

## Fixture Data

- Use `$this->getFixtureGenerator()` in tests extending `ApiTestCase` or `AppTestCase`
- Prefer `FixtureGenerator` methods over raw DB inserts
- Use constants from `FixtureGenerator` / `BaseFixtureGenerator` for known IDs (e.g. `FixtureGenerator::USER_EMAIL`, `FixtureGenerator::ORGANIZATION_ID`) when tests rely on `AppFixtures` data
- For isolated tests, create entities via `FixtureGenerator` with custom data; avoid depending on `AppFixtures` when possible
- New domain entities: add `create*` methods to the appropriate `*FixtureGenerator` and expose via `FixtureGenerator`

## OpenAPI Validation

- Controller tests SHOULD assert responses against the OpenAPI spec when the endpoint is documented
- Use `Phauthentic\PHPUnit\OpenAPIValidator\Symfony\OpenAPIValidatorSymfonyTrait` and `OpenAPISymfonySchemaValidator`
- Schema path by API type:
  - Http: `openapi/openapi-http.yaml`
  - FrontendApi: `openapi/openapi-frontend-api.yaml`
  - BackendApi: `openapi/openapi-backend-api.yaml`
- Call `assertResponseMatchesOpenAPISchema($path, $method)` after successful API calls (path and method must match OpenAPI operation)
- Run `php scripts/merge-openapi.php` before tests if OpenAPI specs changed

## Test Subject Rules

- Repositories MUST have integration tests
- Repositories MUST have 85% or more code coverage
- Facades MUST have integration tests
- Controllers MUST be tested, the use case used by it CAN be mocked
- Any repository that is relying on the tenant MUST have test cases to test tenant isolation
- Use Cases MUST have 85% or more code coverage
- Facade tests MUST be integration tests and mock only bridges to other modules
- Use case tests MUST be integration tests and mock only bridges to other modules
